"Rodrigues","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Luis, Mario, Fernando, Alberto, Juan, Julio, Armando, Eduardo, Francisco.  Portuguese Joao, Agostinho, Paulo, Joaquim, Guilherme, Ilidio, Serafim, Vasco, Albano, Albeiro, Amadeu, Anabela.","Portuguese and Galician: patronymic from the personal name   Rodrigo  . This surname is also found in the cities of the west coast of India, having been taken there by Portuguese colonists. Compare   Rodrigue   2.","Spanish: variant or altered form of <b>Rodríguez</b> (see   Rodriguez  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodriques","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Luis, Carlos, Fernando, Francisco, Gilberto, Juan, Adriano, Agusto, Alfredo, Alicia.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim, Paulo.","Altered form of Portuguese   Rodrigues   and probably also of Spanish <b>Rodríguez</b> (see   Rodriguez  ). It is common in Brazil."]},{"name":"Rodrigo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Elena, Rafael, Alfonso, Alicia, Angel, Araceli, Benardo, Carlos, Carlota, Cristina, Emilio.  Indian Devi, Dileep, Dilip, Gamini, Mahendra, Manoj, Sunil, Tilak.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Rodrigo</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hrōdrīc</i>, a compound of <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, kingdom’. <i>Rodrigo</i> is one of the most important Spanish personal names of ancient Germanic origin. It was borne by the last of the Visigoth kings and by a Christian saint, Saint Roderick, one of the 9th-century martyrs of Córdoba. This surname is also found in and around some of the former Portuguese territories of western India."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pereira","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Luis, Mario, Fernando, Jorge, Francisco, Pedro, Juan, Julio, Armando.  Portuguese Joao, Paulo, Joaquim, Henrique, Ilidio, Agostinho, Duarte, Amadeu, Adao, Ademir, Ligia, Aderito.","Portuguese and Galician: topographic name from Portuguese <i>pereira</i> ‘pear tree’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word in Portugal and Galicia (Spain). This surname is also found in western India, having been taken there by Portuguese colonists.","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Iberian surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Pereyra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Luis, Manuel, Jorge, Ruben, Ana, Fernando, Juan, Julio, Pablo, Pedro.","Portuguese and Galician: variant of   Pereira  ."]},{"name":"Perreira","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Alberto, Alfredo, Ana Lucia, Carmelita, Domingos, Gustavo, Lauriano, Luis, Orlando.  Portuguese Agostinho.","Portuguese (mainly Brazil): variant of   Pereira  ."]},{"name":"Parreira","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Francisco, Avelina, Cesar, Helio, Herminia, Luis, Luisa, Pedro, Valentina.","Portuguese: variant of   Pereira  ."]},{"name":"Pereida","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Juan, Julio, Manuel, Ernesto, Esteban, Eugenio, Felipe, Fermin, Hilario, Jose Luis, Leticia, Marina.","Hispanic (mainly Mexico): altered form of Portugese and Galician   Pereira  , or of Asturian-Leonese and Galician   Pereda  ."]},{"name":"Perera","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Emilio, Jorge, Orlando, Roberto, Armando, Carlos, Juan, Ana, Francisco, Hermino, Manuel.  Indian Nihal, Gamini, Rohan, Daya, Kusum, Mahesh, Manoj, Sonali, Swarna, Ananda, Anura, Ashok.","Catalan: topographic name from <i>perera</i> ‘pear tree’.","Galician and Portuguese: variant of   Pereira  . This surname is also found in western India, where it was taken by Portuguese colonists."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Froile Rodrigues de Pereira was born in 1214, in Spain, her father, Ruy Gonçalves Pereira - I Senhor de Pereira, was 45 and her mother, D. Sancha Henriques de Portocarreiro, was 35. She had at least 2 daughters with Pedro Fernandez Porcalho de Freire e Portugal. She died in 1294, in her hometown, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1214–1294":"1214–1294","1202–1285":"1202–1285","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1210–1291":"1210–1291","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","1210":"1210","1285":"1285","1294":"1294","aproximadamente 1235":"umbes 1235","1291":"1291","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","España":"Hispaania","Pereira, Braga, Portugal":"Pereira, Braga, Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal"},"fi":{"1214–1294":"1214–1294","1202–1285":"1202–1285","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1210–1291":"1210–1291","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","1210":"1210","1285":"1285","1294":"1294","aproximadamente 1235":"noin 1235","1291":"1291","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","España":"Espanja","Pereira, Braga, Portugal":"Pereira, 